fields.content_dutch:
Welcome to Global Signbank.

Global Signbank is a lexical database for sign languages. It is the successor to the NGT Signbank, the lexical database of the annotated NGT corpora at Radboud University, which include the following:

  • ECHO corpus (2004)
  • Corpus NGT (2006–present)
  • Handy Signs (signs for experiments, 2012-2016)

The lexical database does not presently serve as a dictionary. For each data set, specific conditions apply as to (open or restricted) access. By default, datasets are not accessible to the general public.

Global Signbank is open to host new datasets under certain strict conditions:

  • Lemmatisation guidelines and phonological description of signs follows the conventions laid out in the manual
  • Data become accessible for research use by Radboud University and preferably any non-commercial research (open access). In exchange, the NGT dataset will become fully accessible to depositors of a new dataset.
  • A contribution in kind and/or in cash is made to further software development and/or data hosting, depending on the size of the dataset and the expected and actual use

Go directly to:

  • Search (login required)

fields.title: Copyright
fields.content:
Copyright


Content of the different datasets


Different licenses apply to access to each dataset in Global Signbank (select a dataset to see the details).

Site design & development


The NGT Signbank source code is licensed under a BSD 3-clause "New" or "Revised" License.  Onno Crasborn, Richard Bank, Wessel Stoop, Erwin Komen, Micha Hulsbosch & Susan Even (2018, Radboud University, Nijmegen, the Netherlands)


NGT Signbank is based on the Auslan Signbank source code by Trevor Johnston & Steve Cassidy (Macquairie University, Sydney, Australia) for the Auslan Signbank.

fields.title: Manual
fields.content:
A first version of the manual is now available. It describes primarily the phonological description of signs in Global Signbank.


Onno Crasborn, Inge Zwitserlood, Els van der Kooij & Anique Schüller (April 2018) Global Signbank Manual, version 1. Radboud University, Centre for Language Studies.

fields.title: Orientações para sinais novos
fields.content:
Before creating new signs

Before adding a new sign to the lexicon, first make sure you are not adding the same sign form twice under different glosses by:

  1. Checking the already existing glosses;
  2. Checking the field Translation variants to see whether the sign is glossed under a different Dutch translation of the sign.
  3. If the sign can be translated in multiple ways, but you can’t find the word you have in mind in the Gloss field or the Translation variants field, you can check by selecting the phonological features of the sign and see whether your sign is already in the lexicon but under a different translation (if so, make sure you add your meaning in the Translation variants field).

fields.title: Release notes
fields.content:
Development including all bug fixes can be tracked on the Github repository for Global Signbank. New features implemented from 2018 onwards are summarised below.

February 8, 2018

  • A logo designed by the deaf Chinese designer Sun Qian has been added to the header, and serves as a button to go to the home page.
  • A Handshape list has been added, including both photos and a description in terms of distinctive features. The search form allow for searching for handshapes and for searching for signs based on handshape features.
  • ECVs can be exported for each dataset from the page View available datasets.
  • Selected datasets are listed in the header next to the user name. When no datasets are selected, all of them are listed here (and serve as the scope for searches).
  • Datasets can be configured as 'read only' or 'read and write'. Searches for both signs and morphemes respect dataset permissions.
  • The panel Language & Dialect in the detail view has been removed. The Language field is now part of the Dataset value in the Publication Status panel. Dialect is displayed at the top above the glosses when specified.
